snippet.textDisplay:
You did such a good job, what a fun auntie you are! A little idea for next time, something to try out on her... sometimes if you ask kids a question like "shall we put your clothes on then?" They'll say no, because they're being asked a question, and they have learned they have a choice in their response to a question, and actually can say no. If you change it up and don't ask it like a question, ie, "come on we are putting your clothes on now, let's do this then we can play afterwards." They don't have that choice. Some may still say no but then thats more behavioural, as opposed to them being presented with an option of of if they would like their clothes on or not... if they say no and they still have to have their clothes on anyway they can learn their opinion isnt listened to anyway and then become extra frustrated, because after all they were asked, and gave their opinion, not told.
You do such a great job with her! I'm just curious how this would work with her given shes so lovely and sweet!
